papers.abstract:
Pain serves a protective function in acute circumstances; however, in select individuals, pain may persist past the point of injury and become chronic and disabling. Chronic pain is unremitting and carries significant physical, emotional, social, and economic burdens for individuals, their families, and society. The development and persistence of chronic pain is best understood in the context of a biopsychosocial framework. Following a historical overview of pain theories, we present the leading theory of chronic pain, which is a biopsychosocial theory incorporating psychological, affective, cognitive, and physiological factors as key contributors to the development and maintenance of chronic pain symptoms. We summarize evidence supporting the important contribution of each of these factors and how they interact to culminate in the chronic pain experience. We present methods for assessing these constructs in pain patients and discuss how the cognitive-behavioral treatment perspective may be utilized either independently or as part of an intensive rehabilitation approach to decrease pain severity and improve physical and emotional functioning.


Keywords:

chronic;
pain;
psychology;
cognitive;
behavioral
